Resolved Planning Choices

- Should part swapping spend `mana`, `cash`, ritual components, or a mix?: Mana and components which will cost cash or be awarded for activities
- Is `normalcy` mostly a social stat, a risk meter, or both?: A social stat
- Are grades a single global progress value for v1, or should each course track separately?: Course-specific progress is the target model.
- Does sleep simply restore mana, or does it also lock in consequences from the day?: locks in
- Should transformation parts be bought directly, crafted from components, unlocked by study, or all three in staged layers?: can be all of the above or awarded by quests

Planning implications:

- Base game part swapping should spend `mana` and at least one ritual component; cash enters indirectly through buying components.
- `normalcy` should live in the social stat group and should affect social checks without becoming a global alarm meter in v1.
- The base game can include one course-specific grade track to establish the pattern. Later course addons should add their own grade/progress ids.
- Sleep should be a commitment point: restore mana, advance the day, and resolve day-end consequences through authored actions/status effects/quest checks.
- Part acquisition should support multiple paths over time. Base should include the smallest useful sample, while addons teach buying, crafting, studying, and quest rewards separately.
